<dl id="n12187a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12187a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12187a"> 187(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> that length, <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12187a"> <li>FW prototext </li><li><ms href="#n12187a">MS BL 47482b-71</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:021 <a name="rA1yd" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rA1yd">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/r/rA1yd.htm#n12187a">Draft: III&sect;3A.1+</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"> In the beginning the stories are only concerned with dogs, cats and mice, and &ldquo;Madam&rdquo; &mdash; <i>Mevrouw</i> &mdash; is interrupted from all sides with rather striking examples from the children&apos;s own experience, as &ldquo;Once there was an awfully queer cat in our house&rdquo; or &ldquo;In our street there lives a woman, and once a huge mouse, <mark>that length,</mark> ran over the table.&rdquo; Nursery-tales with a deeper meaning follow, and gradually stories of the Old Testament are brought in. <small> G. Van Gestel, &ldquo;The St. Reinilda Congregation of Holland&rdquo; <a name="STRC" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#STRC"><cite title="source">Studies</cite></a> (March 1924) 135 [life in the Catechumenate]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
